Architects have understood that offices also need childcare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides a small nursery within himself to such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outer terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of the employees of Arch.Design can come to her.
The company of architectural projects Arch.Design, of which numerous well-known buildings came out of Brno, thought from the first sketches of the building Avriopoint to include a space for its mini-guard.
The company works around 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and delineators to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, kindergarten is one of the benefits Arch offers.Design to his workers within the framework of his social programme.
The builders and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch's own employees.Design and, with the support of management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund within the framework of the Human Resources and Employment Operational Programme, as well as from the Czech State budget.
Thanks to the funding granted (a total of more than 2.8 million Czech krona) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified staff and services.
When it exhausts funding (two years), Arch.Design is obliged to keep the mini-guard running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the submission of the funding application contributed to the company Economy Rating.
The attention of children is in the hands of qualified personnel; moreover, a nurse and a teacher of the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. She would now host children without age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since this is a \"miniguardy\" it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they go further during the day.
The functioning of childcare is flexible in order to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use childcare, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-guard programme are comparable to the usual preschool education programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive a quality teaching: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach to English.
The class has not only toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their place of work.
Thus, parents are more productive as they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally leads to a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the companies that sign that they offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of staff.
The bone house continues to fascinate after 100 years. Watch Gaudí's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it - the bone house -
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the innovative use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that reminds the scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The front of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought-out order are observed.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, as it is lit in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the twisting of forms continue to surprise us also inside.
Corrugated wood copies the frames of windows, bars, door decorations, mirrors and signs.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district in number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gràcia, emerged from the remodeling of an 1877 house by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of performing a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the House Batlló, made up of several apartments, did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He collaborated in the design the architect Josep María Jujol.
In fact, ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and mosaics used on the facade appeared in his project plans.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of the successful collaboration of Jujol with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Güell Park of Gaudí, in which there are other pieces of it.
Because of their organic form, the locals soon after their completion nicknamed it - the bone house -
Others, because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it - the house of the woods -
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron saint of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with ventilation ventilators and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange for your tilt of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not fully respect the construction standards of the moment and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the municipality was so impacted by the result it requested to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather on the contrary: only fifteen days after the city council's request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery of the second floor there was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented at a jewelry store.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all right angles and lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can be communicated in this way without giving up the necessary privacy for intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and tragaluces.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sun rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or found out, that this is a very beneficial business and extended visits to the common area and the buchtilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entry of other Gaudí constructions into the city.
