More and more parents employ people’s tracking devices to control their children
The fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed to track vehicles, can also follow the movement of people and contribute, for example, to the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
For the moment the device has the approximate size of a zip box, but will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were afraid of the missing Anička case and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of trespassing on your privacy.
“We all try to say that it is not about spying, but about another means of reducing the chances of a tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of monitoring devices in the Czech market.
\"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we haven't met with such cases yet.\"
“Most customers actually buy it for security reasons,” Pilin adds.
In their view, children should always know what the \"box\" is for and how it is used in case of an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns about the fact that, if the child does not want to take it, he will simply throw it away.
\"Even younger children show great creativity when intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid them being controlled\"
“Before, parents relied heavily on mobiles, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device,” says Bočková.
In his view, it is questionable whether in case of attack such a device is really useful.
“If it is a prepared kidnapping, the author will almost always check whether the child carries any type of electronic device that can reveal his/her location”
\"Now it's the phone.\"
\"As the use of tracking devices is extended, it will also seek them, since their sale will undoubtedly be made with much publicity.\"
\"In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police,\" says the psychologist.
However, it adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised pedestrian attack.
According to Robert Čech of the RC Monitoring company, which provides monitoring services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the follow-up device is destroyed immediately, its presence can be of assistance.
‘The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period’
If you suffer damage, at least you will facilitate the last position of the person in question.
The most expensive devices include a tilt gauge, so if the person simply slips out and remains motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question, says Čech.
In your opinion, such a service can be obtained even with mobile smart phones with navigation, where only special software should be installed.
