Support for democracy continues to increase in Latin America, as well as support for private companies.
Crime causes more concern than unemployment.
In addition, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a country more influential than the United States.
These are some of the findings of the latest survey of Latinobarometer conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
As the survey has been regularly conducted since 1995, it allows for follow-up on changes in attitudes in the region.
In the results of this year's survey, held in September and early October, two related issues are highlighted.
The first is the relatively animated mood reigning in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a small 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a great decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents from Mexico and Brazil, the two most populated countries in the area, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see figure 2).
About 44 per cent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably over 25% registered in 2001 (Graph 3).
About 34 per cent stated that they trusted in the Congress of their country and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher in relation to 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it was maintained during the global financial crisis probably meant that many Latin American countries were only affected by a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social security network has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin American people living in poverty is only marginally increased in 2009 and has been reduced again this year, to 32 per cent.)
However, mood varies considerably from country to country (see figure 4).
The good economic performances of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a general sense of progress.
That feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the start of the surveys, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see figure 5).
About 31 per cent states that, whether they or a close relative, they have been the victim of crime in the past year, a figure that has been reduced since 38 per cent of last year and is the lowest percentage since 1995.
The most positive economic returns are reflected in increased support for private companies and the market economy: about 71 per cent of respondents in the region claim that private companies are essential for development, while in 2007 it was only 56 per cent (see figure 6).
Around 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, compared with 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of respondents in Venezuela have the same opinion (and 80% supports private companies), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the country with greater leadership in the region, as indicated by 19 per cent of respondents (as opposed to 18 per cent last year), followed by the United States (9 per cent, same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9 per cent compared to 11 per cent a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered most influential by the respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
