A arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients extends the possibility of finding new forms of life on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although researchers discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say that it is possible that there are life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
“This body has a dual capacity”
\"It can grow either with phosphorus or arsenic\"
\"That makes it very peculiar, although little is missing to be a really 'alienian' way of life,\" said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report appearing in the online edition of the publication Science.
For a long time, there have been six major elements essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“It makes you wonder what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, finding is important for the search for life on different planets on Earth, given that researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated a great deal of speculation on the Internet about the possibility of the report indicating the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery shows is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of elements - standard - which we consider essential for life may not be so fixed - said Charles Cockell, Professor of Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the investigation team.
\"This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element by another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure,\" Cockell added.
The discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA's astrobiology institute, which led the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so it speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace one by another.
‘Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus’
\"Consequently, it can be difficult for different organisms to make them different.\"
“However, arsenic is different enough so that it doesn’t work as well as phosphorus, so it enters and, to say the least, appeals to biochemical machinery,” explains Anbar.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt and use to grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that it may naturally exist a form of life that uses arsenic, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is most common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but no example has ever been found to prove it works.
The arsenic was more common in the early eras of the earth, he pointed out, so researchers speculated that the first forms of life might have used it.
“Yes, it suggests that there might be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth in the past,” Foster said, not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
