Can civicism tend a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for inventiveness and negativity, a bit of civicism has been unleashed in Washington this week.
Is it a portent of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not produce any progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But by what everyone says, it was at least a courteous discussion of the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to win partisan points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the president's committee of deficits was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a trial period, examining each other to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent assessments by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and are deeply rooted to suggest any rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether these are taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are in opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
\"They're inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which then become extinct.
That's good.
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are due at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to extend unemployment subsidies, probably because Republicans cannot believe they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, denying unemployment benefits for the unemployed.
After the Tuesday meeting in the White House, there is greater optimism for possible treatment of these issues during the outstanding session, along with the ratification of the new START nuclear disarmament pact (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation in the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to a continuous bipartisanism when the new 112th. Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable, that a period of disagreement begins.
\"After the things that must be done, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to a confrontation,\" he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to true cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a test for the 2012 major event,” he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As Republican leaders are more aware of the dangers of overemphasizing their position, they know that they must try to fulfill their pledges of cutting state expenses and nullifying the new health law.
These lines of support are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase of certain taxes and retirement age, and the cut in expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have been responsible for one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the issue of deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to reach close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the staff members chosen in the panel, suggesting that there are at least few bases or desires for commitment in fiscal matters at the present time.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will take place next year in the form of partisan shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama with regard to budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of greater two-party cooperation.
What would cause the change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanism of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who considers that he is losing will likely change course and seek commitment.
However, this can be an optimistic vision.
partisanism and polarization are currently greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans of Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, civilization this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common points on the issues that still divide them.
