EU changes rules to get visas
People should visit Visa Request Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and as well as the waiting time.
From 10 January 2011 he will change the procedure of processing a visa at the United States Embassy and consulates.
With the new procedure, most applicants will be required to visit Visa Service Centres (ASC) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
The ASC staff shall take the biometric information of the applicant, which shall be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to make the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another payment to have the courier service deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas on request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for trader and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest CSA where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this less time than in the past.
Likewise, those requesting visas at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of 26 dollars.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101101_Visas-FAQs.html.
