A Global Plan to Refresh Lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancún a plan for the renewal of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GEI) in a quantity that is almost one third of the additional decrease to stabilize the climate of the planet by 2020.
This ambitious plan is framed in the set of major concrete projects that the UN expects to be adopted in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70 per cent of the market, are replaced by fluocompactic bulbs or, even better, by bulbs of electroluminescent diodes (DEL or LED) in English, it would avoid much of the 1,8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8 per cent of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the planetary motor vehicle park.
In Copenhagen last year, large emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to reduce overall GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 gt of that amount should still be reduced to stabilize by 2020 the increase in temperatures by two degrees centigrade to prevent it from being uncontrolled.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, that is, 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is further reduced by two more times.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which allows us to make an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would apply in one hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
Above, they contain nothing of mercury.
Several specialists have expressed reservations about fluocompactic bulbs, since they contain mercury and should be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers place instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not fluocompact bulbs, but coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce electricity that is poured out with incandescent bulbs.
Only in the United States, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save one billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, i.e. the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost it 2.5 billion.
