Revenge hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks issue has a double value.
On the one hand, it unravels an apparent scandal, a scandal that seems only scandalous in the face of hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that each file created by a secret service (independent of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The \"extraordinary\" U.S. revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except Berlusconi) and the sinisterly ridiculous profile of Khadafi has been giving ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be made up of news of public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what was written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult do not just trust what they already know, which confirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informer is lazy, just as he is perishable (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if it could not be, I know, editor of the Liberation), who only considers what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sending the US embassy from Rome to the State Department was the same information published by Newsweek the previous week.
Why, then, have the disclosures of these files caused such a review?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, i.e. that embassies, at least since World War II and since the Heads of States can call on the telephone or catch the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for some limited exercises of representation, have been transformed into spying centers.
Any viewer who sees research movies knows it perfectly, we just seem to know that we don't know it because of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world has a significant impact on the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the \"greens\"
But let's get into the real nature of what's happened.
In the past, at the time of Orwell, he could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control each movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction performed, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power be held that can no longer retain its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public realm; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to take away all power from him.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, since it would be like publishing it on a street cartel.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, confidential conversations cannot be expected on the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has moved by plane and has contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my prediction is a matter of science fiction and therefore, novelism, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at most, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
This information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked boxes: in the end, Watergate's spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing as a crab, that is, backward.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has again created a telegraph with cables (telephonics).
Video tapes (analogs) had enabled film researchers to study a step-by-step film, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the CDs (digital) only allow to move from chapter to chapter, i.e. to huge proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the displacements it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing unusual for politics and communication techniques to take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly being done in the embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies who request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's hats in its pledges of financing
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to consider whether the rapidly unblocked financing promises (called fast start or early start) by developed countries have been respected.
And the French hats have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed themselves to providing $300 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed to providing EUR 7.2 billion in three years and France EUR 1.260 million (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has placed its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press wheel, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was achievable and was appreciated for what was really worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion 2010, which puts it on the right track towards meeting its 2012 commitment of €7.2 billion.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be - new and additional - to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what it means - new and additional -
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the reference that best suits him.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference in 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years as fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of -all new projects - of the year 2010 is - new and additional -
In other words, no reference is made to the costs of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even diminish), while seeking to respect its commitment to new and additional funds...
Another crucial element, the distribution between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no rule and each one chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to a donated euro.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... As much, it should only be computed for its commitments the cost of the loan to the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
However, France does not find such a reasoning useful: \"I respect your commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% of loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of grants (EUR 36.1 million); see the EU document for your own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union that so frequently uses the loan.
Germany uses it in 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union provides a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only provides ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions in time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending as much as EUR 36.1 million, he managed to give the impression that he spent 420 million - new and additional - as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States to continue giving when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a small, relatively short-term, in relation to the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be an extra sand grain in the immense machinery that is the CMNUC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
Firstly, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
However, in particular, France could move forward the discussions on the stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the issue of the ‘additional character’ or the method for computing loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive in relation to this issue as it is with others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of the ‘additional character’ and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to advance negotiations.
